{
  "card_id": "external_liquidity",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "External Liquidity",
  "aliases": [
    "external liquidity sweep",
    "liquidity outside the range"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "Liquidity resting outside the current price range, beyond established swing highs or lows, where stop-loss orders accumulate. Price sweeps these levels to trigger resting orders before reversing back into the range, functioning as a manipulation phase prior to the true directional move.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Mark the current price range by identifying its swing high (Range High) and swing low (Range Low) on the working time frame.",
    "Identify resting liquidity beyond those boundaries: buy-side liquidity above the Range High (equal highs, prior swing highs, Previous Day High) and sell-side liquidity below the Range Low (equal lows, prior swing lows, Previous Day Low).",
    "Confirm an external liquidity sweep when price extends beyond the Range High or Range Low, triggers those orders, and then closes back inside the range rather than sustaining the breakout on a higher time frame.",
    "Note directional context: a sweep of external liquidity on the opposite side of the prevailing order flow (e.g., sweeping sell-side liquidity in a bullish context) signals manipulation before continuation.",
    "Look for the sweep to occur during a high-probability session window (London 02:00–05:00 or New York AM 08:30–09:30 EST) to confirm it is a session-driven manipulation move.",
    "Identify a rally wave, defined as a price swing with a clear high and low; external liquidity is located at the swing high and swing low of that rally wave.",
    "Price often sweeps past these highs or lows to trigger stop-losses before reversing or continuing the trend."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "A sweep of external liquidity signals the manipulation phase of the Power of Three model. After the purge, traders look for a Change in the State of Delivery paired with an order block or fair value gap to enter in the direction of the true move, targeting internal levels or the opposite side of the range. In SMC, wait for a sweep of a swing high/low, then enter at points of interest like fair value gaps or order blocks.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Treating the external liquidity sweep as a genuine breakout and entering in the direction of the sweep, rather than waiting for price to reverse back into the range.",
    "Ignoring the return-to-range dynamic and holding a position in the direction of the sweep instead of anticipating reversion to internal liquidity targets.",
    "Failing to distinguish external liquidity (beyond swing highs/lows) from internal liquidity (fair value gaps or equal highs/lows inside the range), leading to premature entries before the sweep is complete."
  ],
